The reason spiders have "dump trucks" is because that is where almost all their vital organs are located. If that abdomen gets ruptured at all, it pretty much means game over for that spider. It's why many spider enthusiasts hardly pick up their spiders. If they fall and rupture that abdomen, there goes that spider.  Also what is interesting is this huntsman made a web, which is actually very atypical. Damn near unheard of for them actually. They hunt by ambush and camouflage and rushing down their prey when they get too close.

ur done unc Cory DeVante Williams (born November 9, 1992),[2] known online as CoryxKenshin, is an American YouTuber, writer and actor. Williams joined YouTube on April 26, 2009. Known for his comedic playthroughs of horror games, Williams was ranked the fourth top creator in the United States in 2021. here some to think about : Spiders typically do not bite on purpose, and it's not part of their normal behavior to attack humans. They primarily bite as a defensive action when feeling threatened, provoked, or accidentally trapped. Biting is not a way for spiders to hunt for food or acquire blood like other biting insects! so your good.

I would like to share some hopefully fun and not that scary spider facts for the lovely people hiding in the comments, because I enjoy spiders, and wish to make them less scary for at least one or two people, a fact for each leg:  1. Male wolf spiders can purr, they do so to attract mates! Its actually more like how crickets rub their legs together, but still sounds like a purr. It's audible to people! 2.  Spiders have lil paws! A spiders "paw" is called a tarsus! 3. Camel spiders are not real spiders, and they only chase people because you cast a shadow, and they want out of the harsh desert sun! Thought process goes "ooo shade" and then "oh crap the shade is from a larger animal, better bite it to protect myself". 4. Some species of tarantula keep tiny frogs as "pets" or "roommates", they provide the frog with protection, and in turn, the frog protects the tarantula's eggs from ants and will eat any insects that bother the tarantula. This could have started due to the frog in question being poisonous, and then the tarantulas eventually learning that they chill. 5. Some jumping spiders produce a sort of milk to feed their young until they are big enough to leave the nest. 6. A lot of spiders keep their web very clean and will eagerly remove anything they don't want in it. 7. Jumping spiders will play with laser pointers like a cat! 8. Paraphidippus fartilis is a very unfortunate name for such a cute and fluffy jumping spider. Scientists really looked at the beautiful little snowy colored puffball and went â€œhaha, fartâ€. Dang.

I am a spider lover, and a tarantula keeper. I love how X-17 moves and acts and looks like a real spider! Also though spiders do have eyes, not all have very good eyesight. Mygalomorphs (tarantulas, trapdoors, funnel webs) have eight eyes but can't see very well. They rely on their setae (hair-like structures on their legs) to detect vibration. The same might go for certain araneomorphs (possibly sand spiders), however, many araneomorphs have good vision (jumpers, wolf spiders, huntsmen, ect). X-17 is a giant huntsman, therefore they are an araneomorphae. Wouldn't be cool to literally own a huntsman spider?ğŸ•·

TBH, I'm happy to see YouTubers upload full game plays in one go. But at the same time, I don't. Watching full game plays feels like greed really. You want to watch it all, instead of patiently waiting. But in sacrifice, the creator loses out on putting effort into their videos and taking way longer time to edit them out and trying to make a deadline. It puts way more pressure on creators to catch up with the algorithm. Majority of us are pretty much grown up, so we now have jobs to go to, colleges and universities to attend, families to look after, etc. We no longer have the luxury to sit down and watch movie length videos anymore.  But, maybe I'm being blinded by nostalgia. We'll have to see what you will bring us in store for future uploads. Btw, I recommend playing Another Crab's Adventure. And it is also not /incorrect/ to assume that spiders are blind as they are actually very heavily near-sighted and thus tend to rely more on fast movements and loud noises, and being able to sense temperature to detect prey. If you are wondering here are some facts about the huntsman spider. The giant huntsman spider (Heteropoda maxima) is a remarkable cave-dwelling arachnid distinguished by its extraordinary leg span, which can extend up to 30 centimeters (approximately 12 inches), making it the largest known spider species by this measure. First formally described in 2001 by German arachnologist Peter JÃ¤ger, this species was discovered in a remote cave in Laos, an environment that provides essential adaptations for its survival. The giant huntsman exhibits a high degree of agility and speed, facilitated by its elongated legs, which enable it to navigate its subterranean habitat adeptly.   Notably, despite its imposing size and formidable appearance, the giant huntsman spider poses no threat to humans; it is generally regarded as non-venomous and harmless. The discovery of this species has contributed significantly to the understanding of biodiversity within cave ecosystems and underscores the ecological importance of such unique organisms in their respective environments. 1:02 No because lowkey I feel the same way about spiders. I think spiders are so cool, kind of scary but super cool nonetheless. There's a photoshoot of spiders wearing water droplets as hats and that's so cute, then there's another species of spiders that use frogs to protect themselves and that's an awesome partnership. Some spiders also look rocking like the Peacock Spider, the Jumping Zebra Spider, the Eight-Spotted Crab Spider, and the Golden Silk Orb-Weaver. Not to mention they are just born knowing how to make webs! No one teaches them to do that, they just know it. It's like crochet. Some even do something called ballooning, where they release silk strands and are carried by the wind. It's like they're flying.  BUT seeing horrific videos like the ear thing? That one makes me itch, I hate it with every atom in my body. I hate that he reminded me of that video and showed it to us. It gives me a lot of conflicting feelings about spiders, I want to say they're good but then those videos pop up and make my skin crawl and my hair stand on end. So, so, so, so nasty. I have to remind myself that they get rid of cockroaches and think about Spider-Man, silly I know, to make me feel better about them. Even then, I keep thinking about horror stories, myths about spiders, and thriller movies.  Also, fun fact, while some house spider species can survive outdoors, most don't do well out there and can struggle severely. In fact, some will perish rather quickly. So next time you see a spider in your house and use the cup and paper method on it, don't freak out and please reconsider what you're doing. You could be killing your free pest control who wasn't really bothering you. You were living just fine before you knew it was there and trust me, you will forget it was there once you leave it alone. I suggest researching species in your area to see if you can get rid of it or if it's harmful to people. Let bro be your bug-eating roommate.
